<subSubSection id="FC8E653B8744B11E18455154FEC3F69D" pageId="11" pageNumber="204" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="B42B36B08744B11E18455154FCF6F84C" blockId="11.[794,1388,1862,2285]" pageId="11" pageNumber="204">
<emphasis id="86E0EAA28744B11E18455154FC23F89E" bold="true" box="[796,951,1862,1891]" pageId="11" pageNumber="204">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="73944D338744B11E18885154FCF5F876" authority="Osgood, 1900" authorityName="Osgood" authorityYear="1900" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Perognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="11" pageNumber="204" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amplus">Perognathus amplus Osgood, 1900</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation id="04FC3CED8744B11E18235160FCF6F84C" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3802894353" pageId="11" pageNumber="204">Fort Verde, Yavapai Co., Arizona, USA.</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B42B36B08744B11E184451AAFEC3F69D" blockId="11.[794,1388,1862,2285]" lastBlockId="11.[179,1387,2290,3465]" pageId="11" pageNumber="204">
Based on detailed sequencing of nDNA and mtDNA genes, 
<taxonomicName id="73944D338744B11E1F6C51CDFB20F7FD" authorityName="Osgood" authorityYear="1900" box="[1077,1204,2015,2048]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Perognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="11" pageNumber="204" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amplus">P. amplus</taxonomicName>
is a member of the 
<taxonomicName id="73944D338744B11E18DA5E19FBB3F7D5" authorityName="Coues" authorityYear="1875" box="[899,1063,2059,2088]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Perognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="11" pageNumber="204" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="longimembris">longimembris</taxonomicName>
species group of silky pocket mice along with 
<taxonomicName id="73944D338744B11E1F305E3CFABBF7B2" authorityName="Coues" authorityYear="1875" box="[1129,1327,2094,2127]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Perognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="11" pageNumber="204" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="longimembris">P. longimembris</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="73944D338744B11E18455E48FC28F78A" authorityName="Merriam" authorityYear="1889" box="[796,956,2138,2167]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Perognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="11" pageNumber="204" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="inornatus">P. inornatus</taxonomicName>
. Where 
<taxonomicName id="73944D338744B11E1F635E48FB2EF78A" authorityName="Osgood" authorityYear="1900" box="[1082,1210,2138,2167]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Perognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="11" pageNumber="204" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amplus">P. amplus</taxonomicName>
is sympatric with 
<taxonomicName id="73944D338744B11E183C5E6FFBA4F763" authorityName="Coues" authorityYear="1875" box="[869,1072,2173,2206]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Perognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="11" pageNumber="204" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="longimembris">P. longimembris</taxonomicName>
in west-central Arizona, 
<taxonomicName id="73944D338744B11E18165EBFFC58F73B" authorityName="Osgood" authorityYear="1900" box="[847,972,2221,2246]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Perognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="11" pageNumber="204" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amplus">P. amplus</taxonomicName>
is clearly larger. In the north, where they occur on opposite sides of the Colorado River, they are difficult to distinguish morphologically; however, chromosomal and mitochondrial studies support full specific status of the two. Four subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
